To set the height of a `div` element to the height of the browser display using jQuery, you can use the `$(window).height()` method to get the height of the viewport, and then use the `.height()` method to set the height of the `div` element.

Example:

HTML:

```
<div id="myDiv">My content goes here</div>
```

jQuery:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  $('#myDiv').height($(window).height());
});
```

This code uses the `$(document).ready()` function to ensure that the `div` element has been loaded, and then sets its height to the height of the viewport using the `$(window).height()` method. The `$('#myDiv')` selector selects the `div` element with the ID "myDiv", and the `.height()` method sets its height to the value returned by `$(window).height()`.

To modify the `overflow` property of an element from "overlay" to "hidden" using jQuery, you can use the `.css()` method to set the `overflow` style property of the element.

Example:

HTML:

```
<div id="myDiv">My content goes here</div>
```

CSS:

```css
#myDiv {
  overflow: overlay;
}
```

jQuery:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  $('#myDiv').css('overflow', 'hidden');
});
```

This code selects the `div` element with the ID "myDiv" using the `$('#myDiv')` selector, and then uses the `.css()` method to set its `overflow` style property to "hidden". This will remove any scrollbars and make the content of the element completely hidden if it exceeds its dimensions.

To toggle the `overflow` property of an element between "overlay" and "hidden" using jQuery, you can use the `.css()` method and check the current value of the `overflow` property using the `.css('overflow')` method.

Example:

HTML:

```
<div id="myDiv">My content goes here</div>
```

CSS:

```css
#myDiv {
  overflow: overlay;
}
```

jQuery:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  $('#myDiv').click(function() {
    const overflow = $(this).css('overflow');
    if (overflow === 'overlay') {
      $(this).css('overflow', 'hidden');
    } else {
      $(this).css('overflow', 'overlay');
    }
  });
});
```

This code binds a "click" event listener to the `div` element with the ID "myDiv". When the element is clicked, the current value of the `overflow` property is retrieved using the `$().css('overflow')` method and stored in a variable called `overflow`. If `overflow` is "overlay", then the `overflow` property is set to "hidden" using `$().css('overflow', 'hidden')`. If `overflow` is "hidden", then the `overflow` property is set to "overlay" using `$().css('overflow', 'overlay')`. This will toggle the visibility of any scrollbars on the element.

To toggle the display of a `div` element using jQuery, you can use the `.toggle()` method.

Example:

HTML:

```
<button id="btnToggle">Toggle Div</button>
<div id="myDiv" style="display: none;">My content goes here</div>
```

jQuery:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  $('#btnToggle').click(function() {
    $('#myDiv').toggle();
  });
});
```

This code binds a "click" event listener to the button with the ID "btnToggle". When the button is clicked, the `#myDiv` element is selected using the `$('#myDiv')` selector, and the `.toggle()` method is called on it. This will toggle the display of the element between "none" and whatever its previous value was (e.g. "block" or "inline"). In this example, the `#myDiv` element starts with `display: none`, so clicking the "Toggle Div" button will make it visible and hide it alternatively.

Note: the `style="display: none;"` attribute on the `div` element hides it initially. You can remove this attribute if you want the `div` to be visible by default.

